cruitment, this $18.5K engagement is project-specific hiring that can be consolidated with our primary recruitment partner. The Croatian security services vendor at $5K should be evaluated against the office management contract, and if it's standalone, we can either renegotiate or find alternative local security. The recreation club membership at $1.3K is a non-essential employee wellness benefit that can be terminated.\n\nMoving into the insurance vendors, I'm seeing overlap across our HR insurance portfolio. Cici Prudential's $3.2K life insurance can be consolidated under fewer preferred providers, while Cigna Singapore's $13.3K regional health coverage needs careful transition planning since it's actively covering our Singapore employees—we'll need replacement coverage in place before consolidating. There's also a Cision PR Newswire entry in Marketing at $2.1K that's coming through.\n\nContinuing down the list, I'm looking at several low-value facilities expenses: City Pantry's $2.4K office food delivery is a non-essential perk we can terminate, Cleverland Winery Resort's $2.7K appears to be a one-time event venue with no ongoing contract, and Click Send's negligible $55 messaging platform is worth consolidating into our primary communications tools.\n\nFor HR services, the $1.7K Indian vendor is project-specific and can be consolidated under our primary HR provider. Cloud Technology Solutions at $61K is a Google Workspace reseller that overlaps with our other cloud vendors, so I'm flagging this for consolidation under a direct Google agreement. Cloudcrossing is a high-spend network vendor at $209K that needs optimization.\n\nNow I'm looking at the sales tools—Cognism at $27K overlaps with Lusha and Dun & Bradstreet for prospecting data, so consolidating to a single provider makes sense. There's also a $18 Australian supermarket transaction that's not really a vendor relationship. I'm continuing through the vendor list with Collards Chartered Accountants coming up next. ; equity administration can be managed through the primary provider. Moving through the vendor list, I see several more low-value contracts to address: an Indian engineering firm at $1.6K that's project-specific and can be terminated, Croatian airline spend that should consolidate under Navan for unified travel management, and a $2.9K facilities vendor with unclear services that appears non-essential.\n\nNow looking at a Croatian audit firm at $4.1K that overlaps significantly with our larger audit partners like BDO, RSM, and Grant Thornton—consolidating this work under our primary audit partner makes sense to reduce fragmentation. The remaining entries are de minimis purchases: a $35 bakery catering charge and a $30 electronics retail buy, neither of which represent actual vendor relationships.\n\nMoving through the legal spend, I see Curzon Green Solicitors at $1.2K overlapping with our preferred counsel Bisley Law and Pinsent Masons, so consolidating legal matters under those primary firms is the right call. Then there's a small $364 Croatian restaurant expense that's clearly a one-time event cost, not an ongoing vendor relationship. Finally, I'm consolidating the DHL spend of $191 with our existing DHL Express UK account to get unified shipping terms across a single account. Looking at DNS management consolidation under a primary provider, then reviewing a telemedicine platform that can be folded into existing Singapore health insurance, and finally evaluating Docusign's e-signature capability to determine if it should be absorbed into a broader enterprise software agreement or migrated elsewhere.\n\nNow examining logistics vendors where DSV Solutions appears to be a one-time or infrequent shipper that can be consolidated or terminated with minimal impact, followed by Dun & Bradstreet which overlaps significantly with existing sales intelligence tools like Cognism and Lusha—consolidating to a single preferred vendor would have no operational impact. Moving through a Croatian IT distribution vendor that appears to be a one-time hardware purchase. Looking at the HR development consultancy from Emerge Development, it's a $10K project-based engagement that I should evaluate for termination once the program wraps up. Moving on to Entrio Tehnologije, that's just a small one-time Croatian ticketing expense with no ongoing relationship. For Epignosis, I'm seeing an $833 LMS platform that overlaps with our existing Pluralsight setup, so consolidating to a single learning provider makes sense and the content can migrate over.\n\nContinuing through the facilities vendors, Escape Art is another small one-time Croatian entertainment activity with no real vendor relationship. Etm Concessions is a $1.4K UK hospitality venue for what looks like a one-off event or staff entertainment with no ongoing contract. Eurofast International in Greece is an $18.2K legal advisory firm handling project-specific work—if it's not ongoing, I should terminate it, but if we do need ongoing legal support, I'd consolidate under our preferred international legal partner instead. Event Ors appears to be another small facilities vendor...\n\nReviewing the engineering and HR contractors now. Expert-Ing is a minimal $225 Croatian engineering services vendor that looks like a one-time engagement, so terminating makes sense. Fabiola Thistlewhaite is an HR contractor at $2.2K who's likely short-term, and we can absorb those HR tasks internally once the engagement ends. Farmacia is just a de minimis $36 pharmacy purchase in Croatia—not a vendor relationship at all. Moving to the next entry...\n\nFastspring is a $1.2K e-commerce and payment processing platform that should consolidate with our primary payment processor rather than maintain separately. FedEx Express UK is only $47 in spend, so consolidating all courier services under DHL or another preferred carrier makes sense. Fero-Term is a small $131 Croatian heating and facilities vendor handling one-time maintenance, so terminating is the right call. Figma is a $460 design tool that we should consolidate...\n\nContinuing through the design tooling consolidation—either route Figma as our primary platform and migrate Adobe users there, or consolidate under Adobe depending on our preference, with minimal disruption since design work can continue on whichever platform we choose. Floom is just a $162 floral delivery service for office decorations, not an ongoing vendor relationship. Formswift at $301 is a document generation tool with marginal usage that should consolidate under Docusign or our primary legal tech platform. Fortis Trade is a de minimis $95 Croatian supplies vendor from a single transaction, so terminating it has no real impact.\n\nMoving into the next batch: Franklin, Gringer & Cohen is a $427 employment law firm we should consolidate under our primary legal counsel to reduce fragmentation. Freepik at $203 is a negligible stock imagery subscription we can replace with our primary design asset provider or Adobe Stock. Friends Sports Club at $797 is a non-essential employee wellness benefit we can terminate without operational impact. G S Notary Public Limited is coming in at $1,935.46 and appears to be flagged for termination. Continuing through the vendor list, I see several small facilities and service expenses to evaluate. Garden City is a de minimis $45 transaction that doesn't constitute an actual vendor relationship, so that's a straightforward termination. Gaucho Restaurants is a one-time $302 client entertainment expense, also not a recurring vendor. George Anchor is a $2.1K facilities vendor with unclear services that appears to be a one-off, so terminating makes sense. For GoDaddy, I'm looking at consolidating their $923 domain registration service under a primary DNS provider like DNSimple or AWS Route53 to centralize domain management across the portfolio. Continuing through the vendor list, Google Ireland's $24.8K in ad spend should consolidate