evelopers and negotiating volume pricing. There's also a small G&A vendor for $2.2K that looks like a one-time engagement, and a JLL real estate services contract in NSW at $16.3K that appears to overlap with existing facilities coverage. Kimble Applications is a $53K project management platform that's now Certinia—I should consolidate this with our other tools like Smartsheet and Trello to reduce SaaS duplication, though the migration will require handling project billing and resource data. Klg is another small $681 legal firm to terminate and fold into primary counsel. Konzum Plus is a low-value $15.7K Croatian retail spend that's likely office supplies or catering.\n\nKosmaz Technologies is just a $195 Croatian vendor I can consolidate with primary IT vendors. Kryterion is a $3.5K certification testing platform with limited usage—I should evaluate whether it's essential to our talent strategy or if employees can use our main L&D platform instead. Lajnap Comedy Booking is a small $1.5K entertainment vendor to terminate.\n\nContinuing through the rest: Lancefield Bus Service was a one-time $412 transport charge for an event, not an ongoing relationship. Landu Law Solicitors is a minor $568 UK legal firm I can consolidate under primary counsel. Lane Ip Limited is an $852 IP law firm I should consolidate with either primary counsel or a preferred IP specialist. LastPass Ireland is a $263 engineering tool I'm consolidating.\n\nGenerating vendor review table... Continuing through the vendor list, I'm looking at Lunch Nutrition D.O.O., a small Croatian catering service for employee lunches that should be terminated unless it's part of the office management contract. Lusha is a low-cost B2B contact tool that overlaps significantly with existing sales intelligence platforms, so consolidating under a single provider makes sense. Then there are a couple of de minimis retail food purchases that don't constitute actual vendor relationships and can be terminated with no impact