358K—it's the core travel management platform for the entire organization, so I need to negotiate better enterprise pricing and identify that there's a duplicate Navan entity at $58K that should be consolidated. The second Navan entry appears to be cut off, but it's clearly the same platform under a different account that needs to be merged. Looking at a few more vendor entries: New Block is essentially a rounding error at $56, so that's a straightforward termination. New Star Networks is more interesting—$24K in network services that could consolidate with our larger telecom vendors, though I need to check if there's any dependency there before merging them. Niva Transport is another small one-off at $358 that we can route through Navan instead.\n\nMoving into the next batch, there's a Czech beauty retailer for $161 that's clearly a single transaction, not an ongoing relationship. NPM is more critical—it's $3.5K for package management that's essential to our JavaScript development, so I'm looking at whether we're on the right plan tier rather than cutting it. Then O'Donnell Salzano is a $4K Australian legal firm we can fold into our primary counsel arrangement.\n\nNow I'm reviewing a few Croatian vendors: Oakberry is a small food purchase we can drop, the hotel accommodation is a one-off we can route through Navan instead, and the cleaning service at $6.6K is worth evaluating—it might already be covered under our office management contract or we could renegotiate locally.\n\nContinuing through the facilities list, I see the catering vendor is just occasional orders with no strategic value, the London office move was a one-time expense we can terminate, Officeworks is a minor Australian supplies purchase that should route through procurement, and the Croatian vendor at $1.1K is another low-impact one-time facility cost we can cut.\n\nFor Omonia, this $9.6K Croatian facilities vendor looks like it might be ongoing maintenance or cleaning for the office there, so I should evaluate whether we're getting better value than what an office management contract would provide, though alternatives are available. Orcola is another $3.5K Croatian facilities expense where I need to determine if it's actually a recurring service before terminating. Moving to G&A, Orionw is a $4K US vendor with unclear services that's likely project-specific, so we can terminate once that project wraps. Outreach Corporation is a $9.2K sales vendor that we should consolidate rather than terminate outright.\n\nFor Outreach specifically, there's overlap with our Salesforce investment and Cognism, so I'm thinking we either fold this into Salesforce as the primary CRM or look into whether Salesforce has a native Outreach integration to streamline the sales tech stack. The transition risk is low since Salesforce can handle sales cadences on its own. Then there's the P S Recreation Club at $1.2K for HR—that's just employee entertainment and not essential, so we can cut it. Paint & Fun looks like a $1.7K facilities vendor for what was probably a one-time team activity rather than an actual ongoing vendor relationship, so that's another termination.\n\nMoving through the smaller items: the Paint&Wine event at $159 is de minimis and another one-off team activity, Pan-Pek at $50 is just a Croatian bakery purchase, not a vendor relationship. For Papertrail, I'm seeing a $3.9K log management tool that overlaps with our primary engineering stack—Datadog and AWS CloudWatch are already handling observability, so consolidating logging there makes sense and keeps the transition smooth.\n\nParcelforce is another de minimis courier spend at $155 that we can fold into our DHL consolidation. Peakon at $17K is more significant—it's an employee engagement survey platform now owned by Workday, so I should evaluate whether our primary HR platform already includes survey functionality before deciding on consolidation. The Croatian retail purchase from Pepco at $89 is a single transaction, not an ongoing vendor relationship.\n\nPepe's Italian at $339 is a one-time restaurant expense for entertainment, so that's a straightforward termination. PerformancePro at $10K is a performance management tool that should consolidate into our primary HRIS or talent management system to reduce HR tech fragmentation. Pingo in Croatia at $14.5K appears to be IT hardware or facilities supplies, which we can consolidate under our preferred IT vendor. Pink Ribbon Shop at $2.3K looks like a one-time cause marketing or charity merchandise purchase.\n\nMoving through the remaining vendors: Pinnacle Partnership in Canada at $4.8K is a G&A vendor with unclear services that appears project-specific, so we can terminate once that work wraps up. Pinsent Masons at $4.1K is an international law firm handling APAC work that we should consolidate under Intertrust Singapore as our primary international legal counsel. Pixsy at $613 is a niche image copyright enforcement tool that's not core to our legal operations, so we should evaluate whether we're actively managing IP claims before deciding to keep it.\n\nNow looking at Planful at $27.7K—this is a financial planning and analysis platform that we'd want to consolidate with our primary finance systems like Sage and Kimble to simplify the tech stack, though we need to be careful about active budgeting workflows and plan for data migration. Platinum Office in Croatia at $62 is essentially a one-off transaction rather than an ongoing vendor relationship, so that's straightforward to terminate. Pluralsight at $318 is a learning platform we should consolidate under our primary LMS, though the thought cuts off before finishing the evaluation.\n\nContinuing with the vendor review: Plus Your Business at $17K is a redundant digital marketing agency we can terminate since our primary agency and MightyHive already cover those needs. Pluxee India at $4K handles employee benefits and meal vouchers for our Indian workforce—consolidating that under our primary HR vendor for India makes sense. And PMI Global Operations at $378 is just a Project Management Institute membership fee that's not core to our legal or compliance operations.\n\nMoving through the remaining low-value items: Poles Ltd at $10.5K was a UK hotel venue, likely a one-time team offsite or client event, so that's a clean termination. Porezno Savjetnistvo at $1.8K is Croatian tax advisory work we can fold into our primary finance partners' scope. And Post Office Ltd at $32 is essentially a one-time postage charge, not a real vendor relationship.\n\nContinuing down the list, I'm seeing Potomac D.O.O. at $506 as a minor Croatian facilities expense, President Hotel at $803 for one-time accommodation that should route through Navan, Pret A Manger at $92 as a single coffee purchase, and Prezzee at $64 as a gift card platform we can consolidate under our main HR rewards program. All of these are straightforward terminations with no operational impact.\n\nNow I'm looking at PwC at $4.9K—this one's different since it's an important strategic advisory relationship despite the low spend, so I should optimize rather than terminate and make sure we're clear on the engagement scope. Then there's Profi Bar at $4.9K, a Croatian facilities vendor that's likely catering or supplies we can source locally instead, and Puducherry Backwater Resort at $4.1K which appears to be a one-time team event that isn't strategically necessary.\n\nMoving through the smaller vendors: Puzzle Promotion at $143 is just a one-time Croatian promotions spend with no real vendor relationship, Quadrant Law at $1.3K is a minor legal engagement we should consolidate under our primary counsel, and Radisson GRT at $1.4K is a one-time hotel stay we can route through Navan instead. Radius Group is coming in at $1.7K...\n\nActually, looking at Raiffeisenbank Austria, this one's different—it's $920 in banking fees for our Croatian entity and it's a core relationship we need to keep, so I'm marking this to optimize rather than terminate. We should review the fee structure and consolidate accounts where possible, but disrupting this would impact payroll and vendor payments, so it's high priority. Ramiro D.O.O. is $11.5K for facilities maintenance in Croatia—if it's ongoing, we should fold it into our primary facilities contract, otherwise we can terminate it.\n\nNow I'm moving through the smaller vendors. Regency Hampers is just a $248 gift hamper, a one-time client gift, not really a vendor relationship so we terminate. Retriever is $88 from a single engineering transaction, also terminate. Rhea D.O.O. is $1.3K for Croatian facilities, looks like a one-time expense so we can drop it. Rishi Events is $198 for one-time entertainment, not an ongoing vendor relationship.\n\nRoto Dinamic is another small Croatian facilities vendor at $512, one-time spend, so we terminate that too. RSM UK is different though—$117K in corporate finance advisory that overlaps with our BDO relationship which is already at $343K. This one's flagged as HIGH risk because they're actively involved in M&A and advisory work, so consolidating or running a competitive tender would disrupt transaction timelines. We need to be careful here. Then Rudan D.O.O. is another small $473 Croatian facilities vendor, one-time, so we terminate.\n\nGenerating vendor analysis... Salesforce is the critical priority here—at $3.1M it's our highest spend and core to sales operations, so I need to focus on negotiating better terms, right-sizing licenses by role, and bundling add-ons like Outreach and HubSpot for better pricing. Semrush is a low-cost consolidation candidate that overlaps with our existing marketing tools. I'm also flagging a couple of minimal-spend items to terminate: a $55 hospitality charge and a $10.1K insurance advisory that aren't strategic relationships.\n\nFor the engineering and facilities vendors, I'm seeing a pattern of project-specific or duplicative services that should roll into our primary partners—the Indian IT services vendor consolidates under Infosys, Slack spend can be absorbed into Microsoft Teams, and the Croatian facilities management likely overlaps with our main office vendor. These are all low-risk terminations since the work can be absorbed elsewhere.\n\nNow I'm moving through the product and marketing vendors—Smartsheet is another SaaS tool to consolidate under a single project management platform to reduce tool sprawl, while the media sponsorship and photo printing are one-off expenses with no strategic value, so they're straightforward terminations with minimal impact.\n\nContinuing down the list, I see several smaller vendors: an Indian IT systems vendor for engineering that can be absorbed by the primary partner, an Indian employee benefits platform that should be consolidated with potential overlap to evaluate, a UK restaurant for one-time entertainment that's not a real vendor relationship, and the beginning of a Solarwinds entry that's cut off. Continuing through the second Croatian occupational health provider—consolidating all three under one preferred clinic makes sense. Then I'm looking at a few more Croatian vendors: a tech community sponsorship that's just a one-time event, a sportswear retailer from a single purchase, and a sports entertainment activity for the team—all small amounts with no ongoing relationship, so terminating them has no real impact.\n\nNow I'm at a Croatian sports association membership for $66 that's also a one-time commitment and not strategic. Moving to a bigger decision: SS&C Intralinks at $40K for their virtual data room platform. This one needs consolidation with the primary M&A advisors since active deal rooms have time-sensitive access requirements during transactions, so there's medium risk if we're not careful with the timing. Then there's Starhub, a Singapore telecom vendor at $2.2K that should consolidate with the other primary telecom providers.\n\nContinuing through the smaller vendors: a Zagreb facilities vendor for $263 that's just a one-time payment, an individual G&A contractor at $2.3K who's likely freelance work, and a small US legal compliance service at $483 that can roll under primary legal counsel. Now looking at Student Packers & Movers in facilities. Now I'm reviewing the remaining vendor terminations in this batch. Susan Lee is a small G&A consulting expense that can be wrapped up, while the Zagreb student center represents a more significant decision point at $44K—I need to determine if it's a mandatory employee benefit or discretionary spending, since that affects the termination risk level. The smaller vendors like Taste Of Health are straightforward cuts with minimal operational impact.\n\nMoving through the next set, I'm seeing similar patterns: Tattu Manchester is a one-time restaurant charge, the Croatian online vendor is negligible, and the UK tax advisory firm can be consolidated into existing finance partnerships like BDO or RSM, which reduces complexity without losing capability.\n\nContinuing down the list, the Croatian business advisory is essentially de minimis at $129, the IT recruitment agency at $22K should roll into the primary RPO framework, and the Telefonica electronic procurement entity is a duplicate that can be absorbed into the main Telefonica Global Services account, which is already handling $90K of spend.\n\nThe larger Telefonica telecom contract at $90K presents a consolidation opportunity when combined with Cloudcrossing and Hrvatski Telekom—this requires network migration planning but offers significant vendor rationalization. The Croatian cable provider is a secondary connectivity source that needs optimization for SLA compliance, while the conference organizer is a one-time sponsorship with no strategic value.\n\nMoving through the remaining low-impact vendors: a catering charge and cycle-to-work scheme purchase are both de minimis one-time expenses to terminate, the Guardian advertising placement can be consolidated under primary programmatic channels, and there's a plant maintenance vendor to evaluate. Continuing through the vendor review—Tiganda and Till Trade are small Croatian facilities vendors with one-time expenses that don't warrant ongoing relationships. Time Out Group was a one-off marketing sponsorship with no strategic value. I'm also evaluating TMForum memberships, where there's a smaller $510 entry and a larger $57,560 charge that I need to assess for actual usage and benefit.\n\nI notice T-Mobile's $3,357 telecom spend should consolidate under a primary provider agreement, and then there's a significant UK office lease at Tog UK Properties for $264K that's a strategic asset but needs optimization through lease renegotiation and utilization review.\n\nMoving through the smaller Croatian vendors now—TP Prime at $13.8K for facilities maintenance can likely be absorbed by existing office management contracts, while Trans-Agram and Treci Posao are both minimal one-time expenses under $600 that don't represent ongoing vendor relationships.\n\nTrello's $6.7K spend should consolidate into the broader Atlassian enterprise license since it's already part of their suite, alongside the other project management tools we're consolidating. Then there's a small German tech services vendor at $961 that appears to be project-based and can be terminated once complete, and a London hotel charge of $3.9K that looks like a one-time accommodation expense.\n\nMoving through the smaller items: Uber Eats at $50 is just incidental food delivery with no real vendor relationship, so that's an easy terminate. Uberflip at $26K overlaps significantly with HubSpot for content delivery, so consolidating content marketing under HubSpot makes sense during the transition. Finally, the UK virtual mailbox service at $670 should be evaluated based on whether it's actually needed for the registered address—if not, it can go.\n\nNow looking at the wellness program vendor at $2.7K—that's supplemental and non-essential, so terminating it has no critical impact. The uptime monitoring tool at $78 is negligible and can be absorbed into the existing Datadog and AWS CloudWatch stack. The Croatian events vendor at $851 was a one-time engagement with no ongoing relationship, so that's another straightforward termination.\n\nFor the occupational medicine and healthcare vendors, I'm consolidating the three Croatian clinics under a single preferred provider—the $20 and $131 spend levels are minimal and the consolidated provider can handle the same services. The investment management fees at $32.4K need clarification on whether this is advisory work or fund fees; if it's advisory, it consolidates with the primary finance partner with low disruption.\n\nNow looking at the facilities vendor—this is a $39.3K Croatian catering operation that's more significant and requires careful handling since it may be the primary office catering provider, making replacement necessary before termination. The immigration services at $11.2K consolidate cleanly under the primary legal provider's global mobility program. The Vistaprint charge is just a one-time $130 print order with no ongoing vendor relationship, so it's a straightforward termination.\n\nContinuing through the smaller items: the $182 wellness program is a minor one-time expense with no strategic value, the $467 Croatian wine purchase was a one-time event expense, and the $3.7K Australian Vodafone mobile service consolidates under the primary telecom agreement with minimal disruption. The next Croatian facilities vendor at $144K appears to be a more substantial operation that needs closer evaluation. continuing through the vendor list—Winmaxi Tours consolidates into Navan with no operational impact, Wolt is just a de minimis food delivery charge, and Work Easy Space in India needs careful evaluation since employees may depend on that coworking arrangement before we terminate it.\n\nNow looking at Workato, a $16K integration platform that we should consolidate with Zapier or potentially replace through Salesforce's native features, though I need to be careful here since active workflows might depend on it and migration could be complex. The remaining Croatian vendors—Xenon Savjetovanje and Yellow Submarine—are both negligible one-time charges with no ongoing relationship.\n\nYoxel is another minor engineering tool purchase we can terminate cleanly. Zagrebacki Holding appears to be a utility fee or administrative charge that should probably be reclassified rather than eliminated. But Zagrebtower is significant—that $184K lease is our primary Croatian office facility, so while we should definitely negotiate renewal terms and look at space optimization, we can't just cut it without displacing the Zagreb team.\n\nMoving through the remaining vendors, Zapier is a small workflow automation tool that overlaps with our Workato platform, so consolidating them makes sense. Zettanet is another de minimis network services charge we can fold into our primary connectivity vendor. The beverage vendor is straightforward to terminate unless it's already bundled into our office management contract. And I'm seeing the start of a legal services entry that's cut off.\n\nNow I'm compiling the final vendor entries and identifying the top cost optimization opportunities across the entire spend analysis. The three biggest wins are Salesforce at $3.1M through license right-sizing, Navan at over $400K combined across multiple entries that can be consolidated and renegotiated, and BDO at $343K. Once I have all the rationales documented, I'll format this into a clean, comprehensive report.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13051,"cache_read_input_tokens":16187,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":13051,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"30d5f0ff-1d06-4708-924e-f721060f0333","uuid":"a9a4dac4-3bf2-4015-9d62-3cbea7bc4034"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DLhJy5QZM9dABrgBoSx4Mg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the complete **STEP 06 — Vendor Decision Rationale Log** for all 386 vendors. This is an audit record only; no changes have been made to the workbook.\n\n---\n\n## STEP 06: Vendor Decision Rationale Log\n**Source:** Vendor Analysis Assessment — A - TEMPLATE - RWA - Vendor Spend Strategy (R Jegadeswari).xlsx\n**Date:** 2026-03-22 | **Total Vendors:** 386 | **For audit purposes only**\n\n---\n\n| Vendor Name | Recommendation | Rationale | 30-Day Impact | Impact Level |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| (Blank) | Terminate | Unnamed vendor with negligible $137 spend; unidentifiable entity with no business relationship documentation; no operational value. | No dependency on unidentifiable vendor. | LOW |\n| 4I Advisory Services | Consolidate | Mid-tier $72K consulting spend overlapping with 4I Management Consulting (same group), creating duplicate supplier records; consolidate both entities under a single MSA for improved rate management. | Partial loss of advisory capacity; project deliverables may be delayed during transition. | MEDIUM |\n| 4I Management Consulting Private Limited | Consolidate | Low-spend subsidiary of 4I Advisory Services group at $12K; consolidating both entities under one agreement eliminates administrative duplication and improves negotiation leverage. | Minimal; low-value engagement easily absorbed by parent entity. | LOW |\n| 4Imprint Direct Ltd | Terminate | Negligible $2.4K promotional merchandise vendor; long-tail marketing supplier with no strategic value; easily replaced on demand. | No operational dependency; merchandise orders redirected to alternative supplier. | LOW |\n| 6Sense Insights Inc | Terminate | De minimis $76 spend indicates dormant or trial account; no meaningful usage at this level; immediate termination has zero impact. | Account is functionally inactive. | LOW |\n| Acclime Corporate Services | Consolidate | Corporate services entity overlapping with Acclime USA Inc; consolidate both Acclime entities under a single regional agreement to eliminate vendor duplication. | Minor; corporate admin maintained through consolidated Acclime engagement. | LOW |\n| Acclime Usa, Inc | Consolidate | Duplicate entry for Acclime group alongside Acclime Corporate Services; consolidating under one vendor record reduces administrative overhead and enables volume negotiation. | Low; merges into primary Acclime relationship without service disruption. | LOW |\n| Accutrainee Limited | Terminate | Low-spend $39K training/staffing vendor with no clear strategic differentiation; engagement appears project-specific and non-recurring. | Some training program continuity risk; identify internal or alternative replacement. | LOW |\n| Adamma Info Services Private Limited | Terminate | Negligible $273 spend; likely one-time administrative purchase with no ongoing service relationship. | No operational dependency. | LOW |\n| Adobe Systems Software | Terminate | Low $3.9K SaaS spend suggesting limited user adoption or a lapsed trial; consolidate any Adobe users into existing enterprise agreements or migrate to Figma. | Minor disruption to creative users; replaceable with existing tools short-term. | LOW |\n| Advena | Terminate | De minimis $154 spend with unidentifiable service; likely one-time purchase with no operational consequence. | No dependency. | LOW |\n| Aetna Life And Casualty Ltd | Optimize | High-value $125K employee health insurance provider; critical benefit for workforce retention and compliance; negotiate renewal terms, review plan design, and benchmark against market rates. | Significant: loss of health coverage creates compliance risk and attrition; cannot be removed within 30 days. | HIGH |\n| Ag Grid Ltd | Terminate | Low $2.7K data grid UI library license; likely limited usage; evaluate open-source alternatives or consolidate under broader engineering tooling budget. | Minor: developers may need to migrate to alternative grid library. | LOW |\n| Agram Life Osiguranje D.O.O. | Terminate | Local Croatian life insurance at $25K; likely duplicated by regional HR programs; evaluate necessity and terminate if superseded by primary benefits plan. | Moderate: impacts Croatian employee benefits if no replacement is secured. | MEDIUM |\n| Aha! Labs Inc | Consolidate | Low $3.7K product roadmap tool overlapping with Smartsheet, Trello, and Big Frontier in the portfolio; consolidate product planning under a single PM platform to reduce SaaS sprawl. | Low; product roadmaps can be managed in existing tools during transition. | LOW |\n| Akton D.O.O. | Terminate | Local Croatian facilities vendor at $3.3K; likely one-time or low-value service engagement with no strategic dependency. | No material operational impact. | LOW |\n| Allianz Australia Workers' Compensation (Victoria) Limited | Optimize | Mandatory statutory workers' compensation insurance in Victoria at $6.1K; optimize by reviewing claims history and premium classification to ensure accurate risk rating. | HIGH: mandatory statutory insurance; termination would create legal compliance breach in Victoria. | HIGH |\n| Allianz Wa | Consolidate | Low-spend $971 Allianz WA entity overlapping with Allianz Australia WC under same parent insurer; consolidate all Allianz policies under a single national account for premium discounts. | Minimal; consolidation within same insurer parent. | LOW |\n| Amazon (Aus) | Terminate | De minimis $233 on Australian Amazon marketplace; likely ad-hoc office supply purchases outside procurement policy; redirect through preferred procurement channels. | No operational impact; purchases redirectable to approved vendors. | LOW |\n| Amazon Web Services Inc. | Consolidate | Small duplicate AWS account at $5.2K alongside primary AWS LLC account ($106K); consolidate billing into master AWS organization account to capture consolidated volume discounts and simplified governance. | Low; workloads migratable to primary AWS account. | LOW |\n| Amazon Web Services Llc | Optimize | Core cloud infrastructure provider at $106K; negotiate AWS Enterprise Discount Program (EDP) or Reserved Instance commitments; right-size underutilized resources to reduce unit costs. | HIGH: core infrastructure services; removal would cause significant system outages. | HIGH |\n| Amazon.Co.Uk | Terminate | Minimal $1.1K on UK Amazon marketplace; ad-hoc purchases outside procurement policy; redirect to approved procurement channels. | No operational impact. | LOW |\n| Ansar Madovic | Terminate | Individual/sole trader vendor at $1.7K in G&A; likely one-time service engagement with no ongoing contract or strategic value. | No material impact. | LOW |\n| Apple - Amer | Consolidate | Small $764 Apple AMER entity creating duplicate vendor records; consolidate all Apple hardware procurement (4 entities totaling ~$8.3K) under a single Apple Business account for volume pricing. | No impact; hardware purchases continue under consolidated account. | LOW |\n| Apple Distribution International Ltd | Consolidate | Duplicate Apple entity for international distribution at $1.9K; part of fragmented Apple spend across 4 entities; consolidate under Apple Business account. | Minimal; same products available via consolidated channel. | LOW |\n| Apple Pty Ltd | Consolidate | Australian Apple entity at $2K creating fragmented vendor records; consolidate with other Apple entities under unified procurement approach for better terms. | Minimal; product availability maintained through consolidated channel. | LOW |\n| Apple Retail Uk Ltd | Consolidate | UK Apple retail purchases at $3.5K; highest-spend Apple entity; consolidate all 4 Apple entities under Apple Business account for unified invoicing and volume pricing. | Low; hardware procurement continues under consolidated Apple relationship. | LOW |\n| Aquila Remete D.O.O. | Terminate | Local Croatian transport vendor at $1.7K; low-value one-time or ad-hoc service with no strategic dependency. | No material impact. | LOW |\n| Arena Center Zagreb D.O.O. | Terminate | Small Zagreb venue expense at $567; one-time or occasional event venue with no recurring contract. | No impact. | LOW |\n| Ariba Inc | Terminate | Low $1.4K procurement platform spend; if SAP Ariba is the P2P tool this should be absorbed into main licensing; if unused, terminate immediately. | Low; minor procurement workflow adjustment. | LOW |\n| Athlete Service Ltd | Terminate | Low-spend $5.3K support services vendor with no clear strategic role; long-tail supplier; terminate and absorb work into core support function. | Low; support capacity redistributable internally. | LOW |\n| Atlassian Pty Ltd | Consolidate | Negligible $224 Atlassian spend likely representing a secondary account; consolidate under primary Atlassian enterprise license. | No impact; teams continue on primary Atlassian license. | LOW |\n| Australian Payroll Professionals Pty Ltd | Terminate | Low $4.4K payroll processing vendor likely duplicating primary payroll system; consolidate AU payroll into main HRIS/payroll provider. | Moderate: AU payroll continuity must be verified before removing. | MEDIUM |\n| Australian Taxation Office (Ato) | Terminate | Statutory $123 ATO payment; this is a compliance obligation, not a vendor relationship; reclassify as regulatory payment. | No vendor relationship to terminate; statutory obligation continues. | LOW |\n| Avoxi Inc | Terminate | Negligible $178 cloud telephony; dormant or unused account; terminate immediately. | No operational dependency at this spend level. | LOW |\n| Axil Coffee Roasters | Terminate | De minimis $89 coffee purchase; one-time facility expense; not a vendor relationship. | No impact. | LOW |\n| Axosoft Gitkraken | Terminate | Negligible $54 dev tool spend; either unused license or individual purchase; consolidate developer tools under enterprise licensing. | No impact; developers can use alternative Git clients. | LOW |\n| Backoffice Associates | Terminate | Low $1.1K back-office services; likely one-time data or admin engagement with no ongoing strategic value. | No material impact. | LOW |\n| Bakemono Bakers Melbourne | Terminate | De minimis $18 bakery purchase; single-transaction catering; not a vendor relationship. | No impact. | LOW |\n| Bb Football Scouting J.D.O.O. | Terminate | Small $823 G&A spend on football scouting; unclear business purpose; likely one-time sponsorship or staff event. | No operational impact. | LOW |\n| Bdo Llp | Optimize | High-spend $343K audit and advisory firm; critical compliance and financial reporting partner; negotiate multi-year engagement fees, define scope boundaries, and benchmark against alternatives to reduce annual cost. | HIGH: audit and regulatory compliance deliverables are time-sensitive; disruption risks filing deadlines. | HIGH |\n| Bella Operation A/S | Terminate | Negligible $241 Danish venue expense; one-time conference or event facility with no recurring relationship. | No impact. | LOW |\n| Benefit Systems D.O.O. | Terminate | Croatian employee benefits platform at $17K; evaluate overlap with core HR programs; if redundant, terminate and migrate employees to primary benefits portal. | Moderate: Croatian employees may lose benefits platform access; ensure migration path. | MEDIUM |\n| Big Frontier Pty Ltd (Cult Of Monday) | Consolidate | Mid-tier $66K SaaS project management platform (Monday.com) overlapping with Smartsheet, Trello, and Aha! Labs; consolidate project management to single platform to eliminate redundancy. | MEDIUM: active project workflows depend on this tool; migration requires planning. | MEDIUM |\n| Bigshare Services Private Limited | Terminate | De minimis $188 registrar/share services; likely one-time or annual administrative fee with no strategic dependency. | No material impact. | LOW |\n| Bijeli Pijesak Obrt Za Poslovno Savjetovanje | Terminate | Low $11.6K Croatian business consulting; project-specific engagement with no evidence of an ongoing strategic relationship. | Low; consulting outputs can be managed internally. | LOW |\n| Bisley Law Ltd | Optimize | Mid-tier $67K legal services firm; important legal partner for ongoing matters; negotiate fixed-fee retainer or capped hourly arrangements to control spend and improve predictability. | MEDIUM: ongoing legal matters need continuity; transition to alternative counsel requires 30-60 days minimum. | MEDIUM |\n| Blink Events | Terminate | Negligible $664 events vendor; one-time event production expense with no ongoing relationship. | No impact. | LOW |\n| Blitz - Cinestar D.O.O. | Terminate | Small $426 Croatian cinema venue; staff event or one-time expense with no operational dependency. | No impact. | LOW |\n| Boe Croatia D.O.O. | Terminate | Low $814 Croatian facilities vendor; minor one-time or ad-hoc service with no recurring contract. | No impact. | LOW |\n| Bonus Opinio D.O.O. | Terminate | De minimis $120 Croatian services vendor; negligible spend with no identified strategic purpose. | No impact. | LOW |\n| British Telecommunications | Consolidate | Low $1.5K BT spend overlapping with Telefonica Global Services ($90K) and other telecom vendors; consolidate telecom under primary provider for better rates. | Low; services migratable to primary telecom provider. | LOW |\n| Brodomerkur D.D. | Terminate | De minimis $29 Croatian retail purchase; single transaction; not a vendor relationship. | No impact. | LOW |\n| Bupa Australia | Optimize | Australian employee health insurance at $12.5K; critical staff benefit for Australian workforce; benchmark premiums and review plan design to optimize cost. | HIGH: active employee health cover; termination would breach employment conditions. | HIGH |\n| Bupa- Supplier | Consolidate | Duplicate Bupa entity at $22.8K alongside Bupa Australia ($12.5K); consolidate both under a single Bupa account to unify coverage management and negotiate group rates. | Low; consolidation within same insurer has no service impact. | LOW |\n| Bureau Veritas Croatia D.O.O. | Terminate | Low $3.2K compliance/inspection services in Croatia; likely one-time certification or audit with no ongoing contract. | Low; compliance certification obtainable from alternative provider. | LOW |\n| Calm Achiever (A Unit Of Mohsin Ali Vakil) | Terminate | Low $4.1K wellness/coaching vendor; supplemental employee program with minimal scale; evaluate ROI and terminate if not part of core benefits strategy. | Low; wellness programming is supplemental with no critical dependency. | LOW |\n| Capitol Services | Terminate | De minimis $120 legal/registered agent services; likely one-time filing fee; if ongoing, consolidate under primary legal provider. | No material impact. | LOW |\n| Care Health Insurance Company Limited | Consolidate | Indian employee health insurance at $24K overlapping with ICICI Lombard GIC ($6K) for Indian employee coverage; consolidate India health insurance under single insurer for group premium discounts. | MEDIUM: active employee health coverage in India; replacement coverage needed before consolidating. | MEDIUM |\n| Carrington Communications | Terminate | Low $1.7K PR/communications agency; project-based engagement without strategic positioning; consolidate PR with primary marketing agency. | No material marketing impact at this spend level. | LOW |\n| Catering Ivic D.O.O. | Terminate | Small $669 Croatian catering vendor; one-time or occasional service with no ongoing contract. | No impact. | LOW |\n| Catering Muring | Terminate | Low $9.6K Croatian catering vendor; facility catering likely tied to office events; if recurring, evaluate inclusion in office management contract; otherwise terminate. | Low; alternative catering sourceable locally. | LOW |\n| Cayman Islands Government | Terminate | De minimis $56 government filing fee; statutory payment, not a vendor relationship; reclassify as r